   <refnamediv>
       <refname>lag</refname>
               <refpurpose>creation of a lagged matrix </refpurpose>
   </refnamediv>
 
        <refsynopsisdiv>
               <title>CALLING SEQUENCE</title>
               <synopsis>[z]=lag(x,n,v)</synopsis>
        </refsynopsisdiv>
 
        <refsection>
           <title>PARAMETERS</title>
           <variablelist>
           <varlistentry>
 
           <term>Input</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> x </term> =    input matrix or vector, (nobs x k)</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> n </term> =    (kx1) vector of lags</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> v </term> =    (optional) initial values (default  =   0)</para></listitem>
 
 
 
<listitem><para>&#160;</para></listitem>
 
           </varlistentry>
 
          <varlistentry>
 
          <term>Output</term>
<listitem><para>*  <term> z </term> =    matrix (or vector) of lags (nobs x k) </para></listitem>
 
          </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
Creates a matrix or vector of lagged values
if n &lt;= 0, z = [] is returned. While you may find this perverse, it is sometimes useful.
for ts use lagts (see chapter 3)


        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>EXAMPLE</title>
              <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
y = lag([1:8]',2)
// returns :
//!   0. !
//!   0. !
//!   1. !
//!   2. !
//!   3. !
//!   4. !
//!   5. !
//!   6. !
 
x1=ones(7,1);x2=[1:7]';y = lag([x1 x2],1,4)
// returns
//!   4.    4. !//!   1.    1. !//!   1.    2. !//!   1.    3. !//!   1.    4. !//!   1.    5. !//!   1.    6. !
               ]]></programlisting>
        </refsection>
 
